  "id": "5a1e18d3-5061-4d61-951a-8356c926a64e",
  "slug": "summer-edition",
  "title": "Summer Edition",
  "summary": "“It’s 2063 and I hear on the radio, “What you know about that Condense Riddim!”<br/>Music starts to play.<br/>“Summer Edition 2023!!!! We outside and we feeling nice.”<br/>I rush to my closet and pull out a bent box of LPs. Brushing off a layer of dust I searched through, finding Jampuff Riddim, Tamarind Riddim…. I pull out a green vinyl with Condense Riddim written on the front.<br/>The music on the radio intensifies and I close my eyes, finding myself in the middle of Broad Street. Pink hair, pink clothes, pink shoes to match, my friends and I walking down the street like it’s ours. Our hair bouncing with the beats, the sun illuminating our skin. That day we got a good deal from the man selling the newly released LPs on the street. “Tamarind juice! Peanut punch! Bottle water! If you get a vinyl you get a juice for free, if you get a juice you get a smile from me.”<br/>“Summer Edition” was created to capture a time in history. It captures the same kind of excitement and memories that a dusty box of LPs in the corner of our aunts’ and uncles’ Caribbean home captures. I wanted to celebrate and showcase the beauty and visual expression that Caribbean street fashion has. By collaborating with AI, I pushed the limitations of AI’s understanding of “Caribbean style” and “Caribbean women” to create a range of women from different ethnicities, found in the Caribbean, and different styles of how they might dress, with an emphasis on color blocking.<br/>Tamarind, Condense, and Jam puff riddim are releases of different dancehall riddims for this “Summer Edition” record.” — Zoe Osborne",
